definition.value: A benzazepine alkaloid isolated from certain species of daffodils.
A methyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of gamma-aminobutyric acid with methanol.
A sphinganine derivative having a beta-D-glucosyl group at the 1-position and an octadecanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
An aldoheptose in pyranose cyclic form with L-glycero-alpha-D-manno stereochemistry.
A primary alcohol that is heptane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1. It has been isolated from Capillipedium parviflorum.
A 2-aminobenzimidazole having methyl substituents at the 5- and 6-positions and a 5-carboxypentyl group at the 1-position.
A  dicarboxylic acid monoamide that is a hapten and transition state analogue containing phenylphosphonate and succinoylamino moieties.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is pyrazolynate in which the tosylate ester has been hydrolysed to the corresponding hydroxy compound. The active herbicide of the proherbicides pyrazolynate and pyrazoxyfen.
A 7,8-dihydrobiopterin in which the 1,2-dihydroxypropyl group has (1R,2S)-configuration; naturally occurring form.
Riboflavin in which the nitrogen at position 5 is replaced by CH and the methyl groups at positions 7 and 8 are substituted by hydrogen and hydroxy, respectively.
The (R)-enantiomer of hydratropic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid that is N-hydroxyglycine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a formyl group. It was originally isolated from cultures of Penicillium frequentans.

A monocarboxylic acid amide that is 1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide which is substituted at position 5 by a 3,3-dimethyltriaz-1-en-1-yl group. It is used for the treatment of metastatic malignant melanoma, and in combination with other drugs for the treatment of Hodgkin's disease and soft-tissue sarcoma.
A monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group, both sulfate groups and sulfamic acid group of HP_dp02_0009.
A peptide anion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of S-nitrosoglutathione.
A pyrimidone that is thymine which is substituted at positions 1 and 6 by a (2-hydroxyethoxy)methyl group and a phenylsulfanyl group, respectively.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-phenyllactic acid.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that results from the removal of all five protons from the phosphate and carboxylic acid groups of (3S)-3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA.
A diol that is hexane substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 6.
An optically active monocarboxylic acid also having amide and phosphonate functional groups.
A member of the class of guanidines that is guanidine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen at position 1 is substituted by a hydroxy group.

A macrolide that is pristinamycin IIA in which the double bond between positions 26 and 26a of the pyrroline ring has been reduced and position 26R carries a [2-(diethylamino)ethyl]sulfonyl group. It is a semi-synthetic streptogramin antibiotic and often used as a mixture with quinupristin for the treatment of vancomycin-resistant Enterococcus faecium.
A straight-chain alkane with seven carbon atoms. It has been found in Jeffrey pine (Pinus jeffreyi).
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is an analogue of L-phenylalanine having a 2-phenylethyl rather than a benzyl side-chain.
A L-gulopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
